\p{\code{\startverb dynamic-sufficiency\stopverb} is the only non-security orphan in the top 10. It has rich content (Ivan Illich's convivial tools, epsilon-machine state gating) but links to nothing.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Three options}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Delete}: Remove 1097 orphans. Recover 9.2 MB. Forest becomes 242 connected trees plus 5 hubs. Clean but lossy.}
\li{\strong{Link}: Add transclusion targets to each orphan. A \code{\startverb detecting-*\stopverb} skill could transclude from a Suricata rules file. A \code{\startverb performing-*\stopverb} skill could transclude from a Metasploit module. Connects them to the forest but requires 1097 edits.}
\li{\strong{Tier}: Move orphans to \code{\startverb slop/\stopverb} directory. They load only on explicit \code{\startverb skill\stopverb} tool invocation, never in random walks. The forest.toml excludes \code{\startverb slop/\stopverb} from the default trees list. Zero loss, clean separation.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{The transclusion test}
\p{A skill passes the transclusion test if removing its SKILL.md would cause information loss. If the content exists identically in the source code it points to, the SKILL.md is redundant — it should be a 20-line stub with transclusion targets.}

\p{Of the 1097 orphans, approximately zero point to source code. They ARE the content. They have no transclusion targets because they have no backing implementation. They are knowledge blobs, not lenses.}

\p{The trans-triad pattern (transclusion × transduction × transitivity) applies only to skills that are \em{instruments for using tools}. Skills that are \em{reference documents} belong in a wiki, not a forest.}
}
